About The Data¶

The dataset has been taken from Kaggle.

Our Natural Images dataset contains 6,899 images from 8 different classes inclduing: airplane, car, cat, dog, flower, fruit, motorbike and person.

  • Airplane: 727 images
  • Car: 968 images
  • Cat: 885 images
  • Dog: 702 images
  • Flower: 843 images
  • Fruit: 1000 images
  • Motorbike: 788 images
  • Person: 986 images

For obtaining training and validation images from each class, we split the classes into two parts 80:20 for training and validation respectively. This resulted in a total of 5522 images obtained for our training set and 1377 images for our validation set.

In [ ]:
#Model 2 Dropout after flattening and before softmax 
num_classes = 8
# do a batch norm where we have dropout (before max pool after conv)
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Flatten(),
  # add dropout layer
  layers.Dropout(rate=0.05),
  layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
  # another dropout 
  layers.Dropout(rate=0.05),
  layers.Dense(num_classes, activation = 'softmax')
])

In [ ]:
model.compile(
  optimizer= tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001),
  loss=tf.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
  metrics=['accuracy'])

Predict On New Data¶

In [ ]:
sunflower_url = "https://storage.googleapis.com/download.tensorflow.org/example_images/592px-Red_sunflower.jpg"
sunflower_path = tf.keras.utils.get_file('Red_sunflower', origin=sunflower_url)

img = keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(
    sunflower_path, target_size=(img_height, img_width)
)
img_array = keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img)
img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0) # Create a batch

predictions = model.predict(img_array)
score = tf.nn.softmax(predictions[0])

print("This image most likely belongs to {} with a {:.2f} percent confidence.".format(class_names[np.argmax(score)], 100 * np.max(score)))
